"News" can take many forms.  It can be unfiltered information - for 
instance "Trump said this at his campaign rally".  It can also take the 
form of opinionated ranting, like this very video.

When confronting new information, it helps to initially stay away from 
opinion based journalism like Fox News and TYT.  For instance, Trump gave a 
speech on his foreign policy recently.  Instead of watching TYT's salty 
video on it, where they essentially twist his every word to make him out to 
be the bad guy - I believe you would be best served first listening to the 
raw footage of the speech objectively, and determining for yourself its 
meaning and Trump's intentions.  Once you've formulated an opinion on a 
piece of information, THEN it's a good idea to seek out opinionated 
journalism, but one source isn't enough.

You have to try to triangulate the truth.  Look at multiple diverse 
sources, and determine what information is consistent across all of them, 
and what information is the product of bias or propaganda.  It is important 
to be mindful of the particular biases of any media you consume, and to 
take all of it with a grain of salt.  If you are looking for a solid 
anti-TYT channel to test their biases against, I would recommend Stefan 
Molyneux on YouTube.  Breitbart is a great anti-Huffington Post.  If you 
stick to only one source, or a group of sources with the same leaning - 
it'll be very difficult to determine when you are being lied and/or 
manipulated.

Truth doesn't come from the TV, or one history book, or YouTube.  It comes 
from investigation and research, and even then, you'll be lucky if you can 
only get close to the truth.  It's difficult.  The media is rotten, 
corrupted to the core - especially establishment media.  MSNBC is owned by 
the same company that makes military weaponry for the US military.  If you 
really want to have your mind blown, I recommend researching Operation 
Mockingbird.  It will make you even more disillusioned with the media.
